[3] Ecuador: reinfection report
Date: Sat 29 Aug 2020 17:45 ECT
Source: El Universo [in Spanish, trans. Mod.MPP, edited]
https://www.eluniverso.com/noticias/2020/08/29/nota/7959514/reinfeccion-ecuador-coronavirus-sars-salud-primer


This Saturday [29 Aug 2020], the Microbiology Institute of the San Francisco University of Quito [USFQ] reported the 1st confirmed case of reinfection with SARS-CoV-2 in the country [Ecuador]. "The genomes of the viruses identified in this Ecuadorian male with COVID-19 in May 2020 and again in August 2020 were sequenced and demonstrated 2 different strains of the virus.

At the beginning of this week (week of 24 Aug 2020), the 1st documented case of reinfection was announced through a study. According to the document, a 33-year-old male resident of Hong Kong, who was hospitalized for COVID-19 on 29 Mar 2020, was positive by PCR on 15 Aug 2020. The young man was probably infected when he was returning to Hong Kong from Spain, via the UK.

On Friday [28 Aug 2020] a new study was published in the USA detailing a subject in Nevada who was positive the 1st time in mid-April 2020, and after recovering returned ill at the end of May 2020. While the scientists mentioned it wasn't clearly reinfection, it wasn't ruled out, given that some people appear to have transient immunity or do not produce antibodies.

Reinfection with the virus in Ecuador
-------------------------------------
Paul Cardenas, a researcher from the Microbiology Institute, explained that the case is a 46-year-old male who after presenting with mild symptoms such as headache, fatigue, among others, tested positive by PCR in May 2020 at the San Francisco University of Quito. Family members also tested positive and as time went by they all recovered.

Another control was done in our laboratory and the PCR was negative. In August [2020] he presented again with other symptoms much more severe this time, in terms of fever, chest pain, cough, and sore throat. He did not require hospitalization, but he was close to needing it; we did a PCR test and it was positive. Obviously, what one always thinks in these cases is that it is the same virus, that the patient's symptoms improved but relapsed. From the 1st to the 2nd illness period there were 81 days, which suggests the return of the same virus is less likely. The only way to know if this virus is different is to compare the 1st infection with the 2nd infection through genomic sequencing," Cardenas explained. The genomic sequencing demonstrated that the person has a new strain of the virus, different from the initial strain. We began to study this during the 1st 2 weeks of August 2020.

"The strains quite different, they belong to 2 groups of viruses that are called clades, or phylogenetic groups, that is to say, based on their DNA sequencing, in this case RNA, they are different, they have various mutations in other sites, it is not the same virus which mutated in the same person", he added [the phylogenetic tree of the viruses can be seen at the source URL above].

No antibody tests were done for this patient during the period in which he was virus free, but currently, he has a high level of IgG. In the case of his family, reinfection could not be confirmed in his wife because complete genome sequences were not possible to obtain from her 1st specimen.

Cardenas explained that it is probable that the 1st infection did not generate an efficient immune response so that the 2nd infection was independent. In addition, one doesn't expect the same levels of transmission experienced in March and April 2020, because reinfection can also be prevented with the use of masks, avoiding crowds, and conducting massive tests.

"It is something expected, but it also means that we need to conduct more investigations into this...we cannot be confident that we are not going to have reinfected individuals or that susceptible persons will not develop serious disease; unfortunately this virus is teaching us all of the time," he indicated

Genomic sequencing
------------------
Since March 2020, the Microbiology Institute of the USFQ began with genomic sequencing of the virus from specimens obtained in hospitals of the capital. At the time, they named the strain hCoV-19/Ecuador/HEE_01/2020, and it was obtained from the 1st positive patient with COVID-19 in Quito -- a 57-year-old Dutch tourist who was in the Eugenio Espejo hospital. After 4 months of work, the number of sequenced genomes rose to 9, from which 6 different strains were detected as circulating in the country until June 2020.

The genome is a set of genes that form a code that contains all the information that is needed to make an organism from scratch. The Institute has collaborations with other universities and hospitals for the extraction of specimens and genome sequencing from other zones of the country such as Canar, Azuay, El Oro, Loja, and Babahoyo.

As of 29 Aug 2020, 52 strains (21 are different) of SARS-CoV-2 have been detected in the country, while in the world there are 4979 genomes identified.

[Byline: Angel Paez]

--
Communicated by:
Ryan McGinnis
<ryan@digicana.com>

[See prior posts for details on earlier reports of 2nd infections (COVID-19 update (380): excess mortality, 2nd infect, pediatric shedding, WHO 20200829.7727737, COVID-19 update (375): 2nd infections susp, molecular epidemiology, WHO, global 20200826.7717059, and COVID-19 update (373): Hong Kong 2nd infection, plasma therapy, WHO, global 20200825.7712987).

In a Science Magazine report on 14 Jul 2020, https://science.sciencemag.org/content/369/6501/238
(https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/07/pandemic-virus-slowly-mutating-it-getting-more-dangerous) Kai Kupferschmidt discussed the significance (or unknown significance) of observed mutations of the SARS-CoV-2 identified in the 1st 6 months, focusing on the G614 mutation of the spike protein identified by Korber B et al (Korber B, Fischer WM, Gnanakaran S, et al. Tracking changes in SARS-CoV-2 spike: evidence that D614G increases infectivity of the COVID-19 virus. Cell. 2020; 182(4): 812-827.e19; https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2020.06.043), suggesting this mutation enhanced the virus cell entry. What was mentioned was how few significant mutations had been identified to date.

What is not clear in a number of the reports of 2nd infections is the true definition of a different clade and what degree of certainty the mutations identified in these 2nd infection reports are in fact from 2 separate infections. As the letter published in The Lancet in section [1] above, there is evidence of prolonged clinical illness in individuals... at what point in time can one clearly identify these are not 2nd infections, or in reverse, that the reported virus variants are in fact 2nd infections?

As is stated by Cardenas in the article above, this virus is teaching us something new on a regular basis. - Mod.MPP]

